		<item>
		<title>The FCC stands up for VOIP</title>
		<link>http://werblog.com/2005/03/the-fcc-stands-up-for-voip/</link>
		<comments>http://werblog.com/2005/03/the-fcc-stands-up-for-voip/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 04 Mar 2005 13:13:11 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kwerb]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[VOIP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://werbach.com/wordpress/?p=1205</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The FCC announced an order and consent decree fining a small local phone company for]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The FCC announced an <a href="http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-05-543A1.pdf">order </a> and consent decree fining a small local phone company for <a href="http://werbach.com/blog/archives/2005/02/why_we_need_net.html>blocking </a> the ports used by Vonage&#8217;s VOIP service.  It&#8217;s good to see the FCC taking quick action on Vonage&#8217;s complaint, and fulfilling Chairman Powell&#8217;s commitment to preserve &#8220;Net Neutrality&#8221; for broadband applications.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://werblog.com/2005/03/the-fcc-stands-up-for-voip/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>1</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Why We Need Network Neutrality</title>
		<link>http://werblog.com/2005/02/why-we-need-network-neutrality/</link>
		<comments>http://werblog.com/2005/02/why-we-need-network-neutrality/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 17 Feb 2005 15:08:08 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kwerb]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[VOIP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://werbach.com/wordpress/?p=1194</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Vonage, the leading independent US VOIP provider, has complained to the FCC that a broadband access provider is blocking the ports it uses to provide service. I and others have been raising concerns for some time that broadband platform owners will use their control of the physical and logical layers of the network to preclude ...<a class="post-readmore" href="http://werblog.com/2005/02/why-we-need-network-neutrality/">read more</a>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Vonage, the leading independent US VOIP provider, has <a title="Vonage FCC complaint" href="http://www.advancedippipeline.com/shared/article/printablePipelineArticle.jhtml;jsessionid=RBCQRG5Q2SH00QSNDBCCKHSCJUMEKJVN?articleId=60400945">complained to the FCC</a> that a broadband access provider is blocking the ports it uses to provide service.</p>
<p>I and others have been raising concerns for some time that broadband platform owners will use their control of the physical and logical layers of the network to preclude innovation and competition at higher layers.  We&#8217;ve been told this is a fantasy, and that no broadband provider would have an incentive to do so.  Maybe we were right.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://werblog.com/2005/02/why-we-need-network-neutrality/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>2</slash:comments>
		</item>
